196. J Cutan Pathol. 2018 May 24. doi: 10.1111/cup.13287. [Epub ahead of print]Eruptive poromatosis in a patient with breast cancer.Lim TM(1), Weir J(2), Fearfield L(1)(3).Author information: (1)Dermatology Department, Chelsea and Westminster Hospital NHS Foundation Trust,London, UK.(2)Charing Cross Hospital, Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust, London, UK.(3)Dermatology Department, The Royal Marsden NHS Foundation Trust, London, UK.Poromas are a group of benign growths of poroid differentiation derived fromcells of the terminal sweat duct and connected to the epidermis, normallypresenting as solitary papules, plaques or nodules. Rarely they can be eruptivein nature and as such are described as poromatosis. We report an unusual case of widespread poromatosis occurring in a woman with metastatic breast cancer who hadrecently completed chemo-radiotherapy.Â© 2018 John Wiley & Sons A/S. Published by John Wiley & Sons Ltd.DOI: 10.1111/cup.13287 PMID: 29797732 